            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the Luhn algorithm works</h2>
              <p>
                The Luhn algorithm (also called the “mod 10” algorithm) is a
                simple checksum used to detect common errors in identification
                numbers such as credit cards. It does not provide security; it
                only checks whether the number is structurally valid.
              </p>

              <h3>Step-by-step procedure</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ol class="list-decimal">
                  <li>
                    Starting from the <strong>rightmost digit</strong> (the
                    check digit), move left.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Double every second digit (i.e., digits in even positions
                    from the right).
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    If doubling produces a number &gt; 9, subtract 9 from it
                    (equivalent to adding the digits).
                  </li>
                  <li>Add all digits (modified and unmodified) together.</li>
                  <li>
                    If the total sum is divisible by 10 (sum mod 10 = 0), the
                    number passes the Luhn check.
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </div>

              <h3>Example</h3>
              <p>
                Take the number <span class="mono">4539 1488 0343 6467</span>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Strip spaces: <span class="mono">4539148803436467</span>
                </li>
                <li>
                  From the right, double every second digit:
                  <span class="mono">4 5 3 9 1 4 8 8 0 3 4 3 6 4 6 7</span>
                </li>
                <li>
                  After doubling and subtracting 9 where needed, sum all digits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If the sum is a multiple of 10, the number is Luhn-valid.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>What the Luhn check can and cannot do</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  ✅ Detects single-digit errors (e.g., typing 3 instead of 8).
                </li>
                <li>✅ Detects most adjacent digit swaps (e.g., 45 → 54).</li>
                <li>
                  ❌ Does <strong>not</strong> verify that a card exists or has
                  funds.
                </li>
                <li>
                  ❌ Is <strong>not</strong> a security or encryption mechanism.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p>
                In real payment systems, the Luhn check is just the first gate.
                The card number is then validated against issuer records, expiry
                date, CVV, address verification, fraud checks, and network
                authorization.
              </p>

              <h2>Card number structure (high level)</h2>
              <p>
                A typical payment card number (PAN) has three logical parts:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>IIN/BIN</strong> (Issuer Identification Number / Bank
                  Identification Number) – first 6–8 digits.
                </li>
                <li><strong>Account number</strong> – the following digits.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check digit</strong> – the last digit, computed using
                  the Luhn algorithm.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This tool lets you experiment with prefixes (e.g., BINs) and see
                how the check digit changes, which is useful for QA, test data
                generation, and learning.
              </p>

              <h2>Implementation notes for developers</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Run the Luhn check <strong>client-side</strong> for instant
                  feedback, but always re-check on the server.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Never log or store full PANs in plain text; follow
                  <strong>PCI DSS</strong> and local regulations.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use Luhn only as a <strong>sanity check</strong>, not as a
                  fraud or security control.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Luhn algorithm FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is the Luhn algorithm used for?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    It is a checksum formula used to validate identification
                    numbers such as credit card numbers, IMEI numbers, and some
                    government IDs. It helps catch common data entry mistakes
                    before a number is sent to a backend system.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Does passing the Luhn check mean a card is valid and active?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    No. It only means the number is structurally valid. The card
                    may still be expired, blocked, not issued, or have
                    insufficient funds. Only the issuer or payment network can
                    confirm that.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is it safe to use this validator with real card numbers?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    This page performs all calculations in your browser and does
                    not send card numbers to a server. However, you should avoid
                    using any online tool with real customer data in production
                    workflows. For live systems, implement your own validator
                    inside a PCI-compliant environment.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can the Luhn algorithm detect all possible errors?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    It detects all single-digit errors and most adjacent
                    transpositions, but not all multi-digit changes. It is
                    intentionally lightweight and fast, not cryptographically
                    strong.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Which card brands use the Luhn algorithm?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Visa, Mastercard, Discover, JCB, and Diners Club all use
                    Luhn-based check digits. Some private-label or legacy cards
                    may use different schemes.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
